CLASS in JS --
Provides a more structured and cleaner way to work with objects compared to
traditional constructor functions ex. static keyword, encapsulation, inheritance etc.

class Product {
	constructor(name, price){
		this.name = name;
		this.price = price;
	}
	displayProduct( ){
		console.log(`Procudt: ${this.name}`);
	}
}

Static keyword -- 
defines properties or methods that belong to a class itself rather than the objects created from that class 
(class owns anything static, not the objects)  -- We dont need to create any object to use the property.

 class Mathutil{
 	static PI = 3.14159;

 	static getDiameter(radius){
 		return radius *2;
 	}
 }
 To access static variable or function -- Classname.variable name -- Mathutil.PI , Mathutil.getDiameter( ).

Inheritance in JS --
allows a new class to inherit properties and methods from an existing class and helps with code reusability.

We use the `extends` keyword to inherit from classes.
class Animal {
	alive = true;
	sleep(){
		console.log(`This ${this.name} is sleeping`);
	}
}
class Rabbit extends Animal{
	name = "Rabbit";
}

const rabbit = new Rabbit();

// rabbit.alive = false;
console.log(rabbit.alive);
rabbit.sleep();


SUPER  keyword in JS --
Used in classes to call the constructor or access the properties and methods of a parent (Superclass)
this -- used to specify the current object.
super -- used to specify the parent object.

For child classes extending from the parent class. We first have to run the constructor of the parrent class --
using the super( ) method and then we can sun the constructors of the child class.


Getters and Setters -- 
Getter -- a special method that makes a property readable.
Setter -- a special method that makes a property writable.

Used to validate and modify a value when reading / writing a property.

class Rectangle{
    constructor(width,height){
        this.width = width;
        this.height = height;
    }
    set width(newWidth){
        if(newWidth>0)
            this._width = newWidth;    // _ used before the name is used for indicating private property.
        else
            console.error("Width must be positive integer");
    }
    set height(newHeight){
        if(newHeight>0)
            this._height = newHeight;
        else
            console.error("Height must be positive integer");
    }

    get width(){
        return this._width.toFixed(1);    // can use aditional logic too if required. to perform other modifications.
    }
    get height(){
        return this._height.toFixed(1);
    }
    get area(){
        return (this._width * this._height);
    }

}

const rectangle = new Rectangle(13 , 44);
console.log(rectangle.width);
console.log(rectangle.height);
console.log(rectangle.area);    // Although not a property but still can be called like one bcz of the getter.


If the setters are set then to get the properties getters have to be written or else the properties are not readable.


